@jodot159  - I am not sure which third rate American college you received your education at, but you are completely wrong. The English language was developed in England. England & Germany share a common ethnic heritage, which is possibly what has confused you. The English language has other lingual influences, but it was developed in England. Perhaps you are making reference to the fact that modern England became independent from the Roman Empire in the fifth century, or that some history books mistaken state 1066 (the year of the Norman Conquest) the year that England was created. Archeologists have found evidence that England was inhabited 500,000 years ago. 

There is no such thing as a pure language, however Americans have not made English better.  If anything Americans made things more confusing when they started to use nouns as verbs e.g. interview. 

Noah Webster created an American English dictionary primarily for political reasons. After the American revolution he changed the spelling of many words to distinguish American English from British English. Some words were already spelt differently, due the ignorance of many Americans who did not know the proper spellings of word, so wrong spellings became accepted in America.

@jodot159

I've got two words for you "evolution baby!", oh yes that right!. The english language was first used/created/spoken in Britain not America you dumb redneck,Southern Scotland to be precise. Over the years the language just evolved from different civilizations that entered/invaded Britain. There are actually a few different types of english "Old English", this derived mainly from Germanic settlers (Anglo- Saxons). You may now say "Yea! but these guys were not British" you would be totally wrong they settled there and therefore they were British. Enough about emigration laws. So after old english Britain got invaded by many other settlers and the language was even more influenced (Romance(Latin)/Norse/Norman-French etc etc... until we reached Modern English which is used today. All of this aside we have slang which is mostly only accepted/understood within the regional area the slang is derived from. Sometimes i can't even understand different slang's myself.

@tai69 "There is no such thing as a pure language" there is but there are so many different theories to "language origin". (Google this i can't be bothered explaining) linguistic researchers also think Proto-indo-europeans language is the "Pure Language", every single language spoken today comes from this language. a prehistoric language of Eurasia Europe/Asia.

@jodot159 That's right "European" not America your ancestors at this time were most likely still grunting at each other like the apes they were!.

